passages.text: FY25 Review: Cost- out to support FY26/27 Ebit, volume challenges remain; Maintain Neutral
IEL.AX 12m Price Target: A\\$5.00 Price: A\\$5.89 Downside: 15.1%

GS take: IDP's positive share price reaction reflects the higher than anticipated cost- out in FY26/27, alleviation of near- term Balance Sheet concerns and the relatively low expectations by investors leading into the result, in our view, given the multiple downgrades experienced throughout FY25. While the cost- outs are positive in a challenging market, variability and uncertainty in volumes remain with key source regions remaining at risk of further declines and supply limits present in destination countries. Key catalysts include: impact from changes to various Australian policies across student intake, visa prices and English Language testing (late- 2025/2026), Canadian Budget (Sep- Dec 2025), implementation of UK White Paper (late- 2025/early- 2026), SELTS outcome in UK (late- 2025/2026), and USA policy developments (varied). Maintain Neutral.

Result in line with June guidance. Ebit of A\\$119m was in line with GSe/Visible Alpha Consensus Data and within the guidance range of A\\$115- 120m provided in June. Student Placement volumes down \(29\%\) . SP revenue of A\\$367m was \(+3\% / + 2\%\) vs GSe/consensus with volumes down \(29\%\) and within the guidance range of down \(28 - 30\%\) provided in June. Australian volumes were down \(22\%\) and Multi- destination were down \(34\%\) (Canada down \(58\%\) ), reflecting policy changes and a challenging environment across key intake regions. Price rises in FY25 remained elevated at \(+15\%\) .
within the guidance range of down \(18 - 20\%\) provided in June.

Investment thesis: IDP Education (IEL) is a large global player in the tertiary Student Placement (SP) market and owner and administrator of the IELTS test, a leading global high- stakes English test needed for higher education and work predominantly in the UK, Canada and Australia. IEL has leveraged its university relationships and unique data offerings to also assist educational institutions in placing its ideal students. While we expect IEL to emerge from the current industry challenges longer term well- positioned and with greater market share, once immigration policy and student placements demand stabilize, we consider the near- term outlook to remain uncertain with key policy outcomes expected across core regions, limited visibility on immigration stability and risks surrounding demand from in- take regions. With the near- term uncertainties in mind, we are Neutral- rated.
Valuation methodology: Our 12- month price target is based on a blended (50/50) DCF (WACC: \(9.8\%\) ; TGR: \(+2.5\%\) ; RfR: \(3.5\%\) ) and PE Multiple (17x FY26E) valuation

methodology to best represent IELs short- and long- term prospects, as well as to reflect how investors consider the stock. Key risks: 1) Key IELTS agreements can be terminated with 12 months' notice; 2) increased/decreased competition; 3) third- party risk; 4) political risk discouraging international students traveling to Australia/UK/Canada; and 5) worse/better than expected SP and IELTS volumes.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
